@node Introduction "What does FastROM do?"
FastROM modifies the memory management unit (MMU) tables built for an
MC68040 CPU to yield a little more system performance. This is done by
mapping the Kickstart ROM and the low memory area into fast RAM. The
net effect may be a noticeable speed increase since the fast RAM
generally responds faster than the ROM. The low memory area, in which
the important ExecBase pointer resides, is located in chip RAM which
generally responds much slower than fast RAM and is not necessarily
cacheable.

A special service for the Apple Macintosh emulators "Emplant" and
"Shapeshifter" is included. These emulators store data in the low
memory area, which they expand for their needs. Typically, they change
the size of the area from 4096 bytes to 8192 bytes. FastROM will remap
the entire area, no matter what size it is.

For your convenience, the complete source code of the program is included.
@endnode

@node Requirements "What does FastROM need?"
FastROM needs an Amiga with an MC68040 CPU, such as found on the Commodore
A3640 board or in the A4000T. An MC68LC040 CPU might do (which lacks an FPU),
but an MC68EC040 CPU will not (it lacks an MMU). Since the MC68040 and
MC68060 MMUs are so similar in operation, FastROM might also work with
the MC68060.

Kickstart 2.04 is the first Amiga operating system release that actually
supports the MC68040. Thus, you need Kickstart 2.04 or higher to use
FastROM.

Since FastROM cannot create MMU tables, it just modifies existing tables,
the "SetPatch" tool must have been run first. This normally happens during
the execution of the Startup-Sequence at system startup time.

As pages are mapped into fast RAM, your Amiga needs to have at least
530.000 bytes of fast memory available at the time FastROM is run.
@endnode

@node Installation "How to install FastROM?"
Installation is pretty straightforward: copy FastROM to the C: drawer and
add the following line to the S:User-Startup file:

   C:FastROM >NIL:

It's as simple as that. Keep in mind that FastROM must be started after
the "SetPatch" tool.

You can turn off the translation later by entering

   FastROM OFF
@endnode

@node Problems "What if FastROM does not work?"
If FastROM fails to work correctly, you will most likely see an error message.
Here is the list of error messages and their meanings:

· No 68040 CPU found.

  FastROM is not compatible with the CPU your Amiga has installed.


· Could not create access semaphore.
  Not enough memory for remapping.

  There is not enough memory available.


· Sorry, MMU translation is disabled.

  "SetPatch" has not been run or your Amiga has an MC68EC040 CPU
  installed (unlikely).


· Sorry, supervisor and user root pointers do not match.

  Different MMU tables can be built for two different operating modes
  of the CPU. FastROM requires that the same table is used for both
  of these modes.


· Fast ROM translation is already enabled.

  You cannot activate the fast ROM translation if it is already active.


· The ROM mapping table is not pointing to valid memory.
  The low memory mapping table is not pointing to valid memory.

  The MMU tables cannot be modified since some pages do not point to
  memory. Debugging tools like "Enforcer" or "CyberGuard" may be running.
  FastROM cannot do its job while these tools are active.


· The ROM has already been remapped.
  The low memory area has already been remapped

  A different tool has already enabled address translation for the ROM
  or the low memory area.
@endnode

